  "summary": "Hercule Poirot visits the home of Eve and Guy Carpenter to investigate the murder of Mrs. McGinty, a cleaning lady who was killed the previous November. Eve, a beautiful woman with platinum hair and cold blue eyes, initially claims she does not know Mrs. McGinty. However, Poirot notes that Mrs. McGinty worked at the house every Friday while Eve was living at the Cottage. Eve eventually admits she remembers the murder but dismisses the victim as a \"silly old woman\" who was killed for hiding money under the floor.\n\nWhen Poirot mentions the *Sunday Comet*, Eve becomes visibly agitated and calls for her husband. Guy Carpenter, a tall, arrogant man and public figure, enters the room. He expresses skepticism regarding Poirot's independent investigation, suggesting the case is closed and dismissing the motive as simple robbery. During the exchange, Eve makes a slip of the tongue, stating that Mrs. McGinty was a \"terrible liar.\" Poirot identifies this as a significant clue, prompting Eve to clarify that the woman merely engaged in \"silly gossip\" about others.\n\nLater, Poirot meets with Inspector Spence to discuss the case. They reflect on the obvious nature of the original robbery investigation, which overlooked a clipped newspaper and an ink bottle. Spence presents four faded original photographs from the *Sunday Comet* depicting a woman in a bell-shaped hat with roses. The two men conclude that the woman in the photographs is not Vera Black, as her presence in Broadhurst would have been widely known.",
